https://jdmdh.episciences.org/11090 Estelle Guéville, David Joseph Wrisley, Transcribing Medieval Manuscripts for Machine Learning, in: Journal of Data mining & Digital Humanities, 2 July 2024, On the Way to the Future of Digital Manuscript Studies

Tools to start with
https://www.laurenceanthony.net/software/antconc/  AntConc, a software package that allows statistical analyses on text
https://voyant-tools.org/  Voyant Tools  
https://claude.ai - AI Chatbot

Text databases
https://cema.lamop.fr/search/#page-content CEMA Cartae Europae Medii Aevi (lemmatized corpus) using a NoSketch Engine
https://lta.bbaw.de/  Latin Text Archive 
https://mlat.uzh.ch/browser?path=/  Corpus Corporum (largest text repository on the internet)
https://lila-erc.eu/#page-top - Linking Latin. Building a Knowledge Base of Linguistic Resources for Latin

Guides - Learning material
https://programminghistorian.org/ Programming historian website (English, Spanish, French, Portuguese) – lessons and tutorial for many aspects of Digital Humanities 
https://fortext.net/  Digitale Textanalyse ( in German) excellent entry point, offers orientation and lessons (Darmstadt University)
https://guides.temple.edu/c.php?g=78518&p=505212  Introduction to Text Analysis (Temple University) 
https://libguides.union.edu/digital-scholarship/cta#:~:text=Computational%20Text%20Analysis%20%28CTA%29%20is%20an%20umbrella%20term,texts%2C%20from%20individual%20texts%20to%20big%20%28textual%29%20data. Digital Scholarship: Computational Text Analysis
https://cjbarrie.github.io/CTA-ED/  Computational Text Analysis by Christopher Barrie – textbook with GitHub-repository for self-learning
https://guides.library.illinois.edu/c.php?g=405110&p=2803418 Guide to text mining tools from the University of Illinois

